=========================================
C++17 std::optional
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

What is std::optional?

std::optional was introduced in C++17 to eliminate magic return values like
-1, nullptr, or an empty string.

Instead of guessing whether a returned value is valid, the function explicitly
represents whether a value is present or absent.

Header

#include <optional>

Syntax

std::optional<T>

-----------------------------------------

Problem Before C++17

Functions often returned special values (magic values) to indicate failure.

Example

int getAge(string name)
{
    if(name == "Pavan")
        return 30;

    return -1;      // Employee not found
}

Usage

int age = getAge("Rahul");

if(age == -1)
    cout << "Employee not found";
else
    cout << age;

Problems

• What if -1 is a valid value?
• Caller must know that -1 means "Not Found".
• APIs become ambiguous and error-prone.

This is called the Magic Value Problem.

-----------------------------------------

C++17 Solution

Instead of returning fake values,
return an optional value.

optional<int> getAge(string name)
{
    if(name == "Pavan")
        return 30;

    return std::nullopt;
}

Usage

auto age = getAge("Rahul");

if(age)
{
    cout << *age;
}
else
{
    cout << "Employee not found";
}

Output

Employee not found

---------------------------------
--------

Why *age?*********VVVVVVIMP

The return type is

optional<int>

NOT

int

So,

auto age = getAge("Rahul");

creates

optional<int> age;

To access the actual integer stored inside the optional,
use

*age

or

age.value()

Example

optional<int> age = 30;

cout << *age;          // 30

or

cout << age.value();   // 30

Note

Calling value() on an empty optional throws

std::bad_optional_access

-----------------------------------------

Conceptually

Before C++17

Function returns

30

or

-1

You must guess what -1 means.

-----------------------------------------

With C++17

Function returns

optional<int>

+------------------+
| Value = 30       |
+------------------+

OR

+------------------+
| Empty Box        |
+------------------+

Now the meaning is obvious.

✓ Box contains a value

OR

✓ Box is empty

No guessing.
No magic values.

-----------------------------------------

How to Check

Method 1 (Most Common)

if(opt)
{
    cout << *opt;
}

Method 2

if(opt.has_value())
{
    cout << opt.value();
}

-----------------------------------------

Useful Functions

has_value()

Checks whether a value exists.

-------------------------

value()

Returns the stored value.

Throws std::bad_optional_access if empty.

-------------------------

value_or(default)

Returns stored value.

Otherwise returns the supplied default.

Example

cout << opt.value_or(100);

-------------------------

reset()

Removes the stored value.

-------------------------

emplace()

Constructs a value in-place.

-----------------------------------------

Advantages

• Eliminates magic values
• Removes ambiguity
• Makes APIs expressive
• Safer than special return values
• Improves readability
• Clearly represents "value may or may not exist"

-----------------------------------------

Real-Time Use Cases

