Interview Questions

Q. What is std::optional?

Answer

std::optional is a C++17 wrapper that represents an object that may or may not contain a value.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Why was std::optional introduced?

Answer

Before C++17, functions returned magic values such as -1, nullptr, or an empty string to indicate failure.
These values could also be valid results, causing ambiguity. std::optional explicitly represents whether a value exists,
eliminating this ambiguity.

-----------------------------------------

Q. How do you check whether an optional contains a value?

Answer

if(opt)

or

opt.has_value()

-----------------------------------------

Q. How do you access the stored value?

Answer

*opt

or

opt.value()

-----------------------------------------

Q. What is value_or()?********

Answer

Returns the stored value if present; otherwise returns the supplied default value.

-----------------------------------------

Q. What happens if value() is called on an empty optional?

Answer

It throws

std::bad_optional_access

-----------------------------------------

Q. std::optional vs nullptr?

Answer

nullptr represents the absence of a pointer.

std::optional represents the absence of any type such as int, double, string, or user-defined objects.

