30-Second Interview Answer

"std::optional was introduced in C++17 to solve the Magic Value Problem. 
Before C++17, functions returned special values like -1, nullptr, or an empty string to 
indicate failure, but those values could also be valid results, making APIs ambiguous. 

std::optional<T> explicitly represents whether a value exists or not.
The caller checks using if(optional) or has_value(), and accesses the value using *optional or value(). 
This makes APIs safer, clearer, and more expressive."

